<div id="review_3859860442" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3859860442" />
    <a title="Swaroop" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/100264072-swaroop"><img alt="Swaroop" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1621672092p2/100264072.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3859860442?book_show_action=true">Feb 26, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Swaroop" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Swaroop" href="/user/show/100264072-swaroop">Swaroop</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9781451621389" href="/book/show/17225848-brain-on-fire">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3859860442" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer9134778565713793657"><i>&quot;a touch of madness...&quot;<br/><br/>&quot;We are in the end the sum of our parts, and when the body fails, all the virtues we hold dear go with it.&quot; </i><br/><br/><i>Brain of Fire: My Month of Madness</i> is a memoir written by Susannah Cahalan. The writer, who was working for the New York Post at that time, details in the book her struggle with a rare form of auto-immune disease, which is a type of brain inflammation, called encephalitis. The book is well-written – informative, engaging and valuable. <br/><br/>As the author herself points out</span>
  <span id="freeText9134778565713793657" style="display:none"><i>"a touch of madness..."<br><br>"We are in the end the sum of our parts, and when the body fails, all the virtues we hold dear go with it." </i><br><br><i>Brain of Fire: My Month of Madness</i> is a memoir written by Susannah Cahalan. The writer, who was working for the New York Post at that time, details in the book her struggle with a rare form of auto-immune disease, which is a type of brain inflammation, called encephalitis. The book is well-written – informative, engaging and valuable. <br><br>As the author herself points out, her recovery from the disease can be considered as one of the rarest cases, as despite being misdiagnosed by various well-known physicians and psychologists, Susannah Cahalan was fortunate to be treated and then rightly diagnosed due to the efforts of several physicians at the NYU hospital, including the Syrian-American neurologist, Dr Souhel Najjar. <br><br>This life story points out that it is so important to understand and properly diagnose every case, by giving individual attention to personal circumstances. It is also vital not to prejudge the symptoms – indicators such as psychosis, delusions and hallucinations need not always be a mental disorder like schizophrenia, bipolar or schizoaffective. This memoir also gives hope that when diagnosed and treated properly, the affected person can recover completely and lead a normal life.<br><br><u>Here`s my true and sincere wish</u>::<br><i>
  <b>When in need, may everyone be fortunate to find a sensible and sensitive doctor (like Dr Najjar), who truly ‘listens` and understands! </b>
</i><br><br><img src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1615575412i/31002612.jpg" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><br>(The Good Doctor, © Aastha Soni)</span>
  <a data-text-id="9134778565713793657" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


