<span id="freeTextContainer1756332239323128651">This was a moving account of the terrifying experience writer Susannah Cahalan had with a rare/invisible illness that ravaged her body, causing seizures and delusions, and which none of her doctors could diagnose. Rare/invisible illness can be especially traumatic for patients because not only are you sick, but all your medical tests, sometimes dozens of medical tests, are coming back “normal.” You get accused of making up symptoms. Your symptoms get classified as “psychiatric.” It took months o</span>
  <span id="freeText1756332239323128651" style="display:none">This was a moving account of the terrifying experience writer Susannah Cahalan had with a rare/invisible illness that ravaged her body, causing seizures and delusions, and which none of her doctors could diagnose. Rare/invisible illness can be especially traumatic for patients because not only are you sick, but all your medical tests, sometimes dozens of medical tests, are coming back “normal.” You get accused of making up symptoms. Your symptoms get classified as “psychiatric.” It took months of searching and a determined doctor to finally figure out the root cause of Cahalan’s illness. This is a short medical memoir and a very good one. <br /><br />Please excuse typos/name misspellings. Entered on screen reader.</span>
  <a data-text-id="1756332239323128651" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

